{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17647299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17647299"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:42:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:42:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18239"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18239","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18239"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.71,0.13,0,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10953"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79200"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10953","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10953"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18239"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64552"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25454"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25458"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79200","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79200"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn overuse injury involving eccentric overload at the origin of the common extensor tendon is characterised by pain and tenderness over the lateral aspect of the elbow. This condition is often seen in individuals who perform repetitive wrist extension and gripping activities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following conditions is described by this scenario?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Olecranon bursitis","Lateral epicondylitis","Medial epicondylitis","Intersection syndrome","De Quervain\u0027s tenosynovitis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe condition described is \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral epicondylitis\u003C/strong\u003E, commonly known as tennis elbow. It is an overuse injury resulting from eccentric overload of the extensor muscles, particularly the extensor carpi radialis brevis, at the lateral epicondyle of the humerus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedial epicondylitis\u003C/strong\u003E also known as golfer\u0027s elbow, affects the flexor tendons at the medial epicondyle\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDe Quervain\u0027s tenosynovitis\u003C/strong\u003E involves inflammation of the tendons on the thumb side of the wrist\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntersection syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is an overuse injury affecting the forearm, where the tendons of the first and second dorsal compartments intersect\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOlecranon bursitis\u003C/strong\u003E involves inflammation of the bursa located over the olecranon process of the elbow\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lateral epicondylitis, also known as tennis elbow, is an overuse injury involving the common extensor tendon at the lateral epicondyle of the humerus.","The condition is characterised by pain and tenderness over the lateral aspect of the elbow, often exacerbated by wrist extension and gripping activities.","Eccentric overload of the extensor muscles, particularly the extensor carpi radialis brevis, is a common cause of lateral epicondylitis."],"references":["Buchanan BK, Varacallo M. Lateral Epicondylitis (Tennis Elbow). 2023 Aug 4. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28613744.","Dincer, F., \u0026 Samut, G. (2014). Physical examination of the hand. In Hand function: A practical guide to assessment (pp. 23-40). New York, NY: Springer New York","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wojdyla, L., Hughes, T., \u0026 Stelitano, G. (2023). Hand Pathologies. In Textbook of Musculoskeletal Disorders (pp. 675-689). Cham: Springer International Publishing","Mohan, H. (2018). Textbook of pathology. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64552"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18239"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64552","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64552"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T17:19:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T17:20:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10953"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79200"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)